@iscotchdotca There are but it‚Äôs impossible at times to know or regulate if you aren‚Äôt the one doing the booking. And I don‚Äôt want to avoid places that I love eating at that might happen to have 250+ employees because it‚Äôs exhausting and it still means I have to consciously factor it in.

And for people who think this is helpful -maybe it is if you eat out regularly. But I‚Äôd expect anyone doing this to have a rough sense of nutrition anyway. I don‚Äôt have an eating disorder but if this starts off a spiral for me I am horrified to think what it must be like for them

I don‚Äôt eat out because I‚Äôm trying to calorie control or even as part of a healthy diet. I eat out because I love food. And the rest of the time I maintain a healthy eating pattern. This approach allows for zero f**king nuance around food, and has made the entire thing unpleasant

So now as much as I try it‚Äôs inescapable. It‚Äôll affect what I order, and even then I will be thinking about it at various points of the day. Eating out for me is a pleasure and a joy, and meant to be fun but this has sucked all the enjoyment out of it, and worse, made me fearful.

Calories on menus. This is the second time I‚Äôve eaten out in a fortnight and the menu has the calories on them. I thought I was going to a local pub but it‚Äôs owned by a chain so I couldn‚Äôt pre-empt the menu having it on there. Asked for a menu without, they don‚Äôt have them.

The standout pieces are unravelling all the toxic PE stuff, reconnecting your body and mind after a major event like illness, menopause, giving birth. Framing movement in a way that has FA to do with weight loss. Being proud and excited of growing older.

A lot of people who read this book found it cathartic - it features my story and interviews with 50 others - but it prompts you to look at your own life and to offer compassion for yourself. It is the arm around you saying it‚Äôs not fair, it‚Äôs not right but we can change it.

3) arming you with insight so that you can rebuild your sense of self in a way that is what you need and want, not what someone else is telling you. It is the strongest, most powerful thing you can do for yourself.

2) understanding the gender sports gap isn‚Äôt just about physical fitness but permeates every single area of our lives - advocating for ourselves, feeling empowered, taking risks and trying new things, practising self love and most important being loving to others.

So to other single folk, I feel you, I see you. And don‚Äôt put up with anyone‚Äôs pity, or be made to feel as if you‚Äôre a sad sack who isn‚Äôt enough without another person. Maybe it will happen, maybe it won‚Äôt. But you know you'll be okay either way.

As someone who is single by choice, I love being in a relationship, how incredible being loved feels. But I also know how catastrophic it can be, if you feel you aren‚Äôt enough, and you look to someone else to fill that void.

But most important of all is‚Ä¶ not settling down with the wrong person because you feel like being single is bad by default. Or because you are worried of being alone. I have felt more alone with partners than I ever felt just being by myself.

It‚Äôs just saying that being single isn‚Äôt a bad thing. That actually, actively owning it brings a ton of good things. Financial choices. Self awareness and care. Sanity. Generosity of time and love for your friends and family.

It‚Äôs also utterly inane that people think that‚Äôs a choice you‚Äôre making forever after. Like who makes a choice that they will stick to until they die? Even marriage, that is supposed to last forever, doesn‚Äôt always. A personal choice doesn‚Äôt mean it can‚Äôt or won‚Äôt change.

It‚Äôs not anti-relationships, it‚Äôs not saying NEVER to a relationship. It‚Äôs just saying that you are waiting for the right person, because you do not need another person to complete you. Another person should only ever amplify what you already are.

Single by choice is a perspective shift. It‚Äôs not purgatory where you put your life choices on hold because you‚Äôre waiting for someone else. It‚Äôs not a secondary state, it's seeing yourself as the primary. It radically shifts what and how you make choices.

As an essay of mine is out today in a book about singlehood, and it reminds me of the most basic response from ppl who can't believe you'd choose to be single - 'what, so you never want to be in a relationship, like EVER?' That's not what single by choice means. Not to me anyway.

You might feel you need a ‚Äòbig‚Äô goal to finally make that change but have faith in yourself and trust that you already want this change. It doesn‚Äôt mean you can‚Äôt dream big but give yourself the best chance of success. And 100% that will something you can realistically stick to.

6) Ok ACTUALLY lastly - when I radically changed my Xmas after my husband died, the world didn't end. People didn't stop having fun. It was ok, and I got to have a pressure-free day where I didn't have to pretend to be happy. Life changed, and now I am actually happy. ‚ù§Ô∏è

5) And lastly, do the holiday season in a way that's right for you, ESPECIALLY if you're struggling. Don't isolate yourself but also don't feel pressured to do things you don't want. If you want to spend the day eating wotsits and watching TV reruns, do whatever you need to.

4) Do not go along with things just because 'that's how it's always been done.' Traditions are great, but if going along to some big party or taking part in something makes your brain scream, that is a sign that this is the year to sit it out.

3) Support groups. Depending on what you're struggling with, support groups are a lifeline at this time. They make you feel less alone, help you to voice your isolation and conflict at not feeling so sparkly.

2) Social media. I wish I was a bigger person but pictures of people Having The Best Time Ever on a day when I'm grieving or feeling raw, make me feel worse. Don't be afraid to mute these accounts (or unfollow) if you need to. Think of it as a door you just can't open right now.

1b) I only cancel if I socially cannot deal with it (usually I know what that limit is) versus feeling lazy and not wanting to leave my flat. The idea isn't to be inconsiderate (eg cancelling dinner parties isn't cool) but to give yourself room to disconnect if you need it.

1) Social engagements. I manage this strongly. The idea of the whole of December being booked out makes me want to barf. I either give myself breathing room days in between or I give myself licence to cancel. Mental health is still...health. if it's bad, I have to take measures.

I celebrate this time of year but I also have a list of things to preserve my own sanity and make sure I'm not getting suckered into things that make it any harder than it already is. So without further ado...

I love this time of year for a million reasons, but as with a lot of other people, it can be extremely complicated and a Tough Time. People who've had/have addicted loved ones, those who struggle themselves, ppl with chaotic parents, bereavement dates - the list is endless.
